eat her ice cream,

07:43.790 --> 07:44.930
go home to another beating.

07:47.540 --> 07:48.620
Usual, Judge?

07:48.620 --> 07:50.690
Yeah, thanks.

07:50.690 --> 07:52.775
Walden, you hungry?

07:52.775 --> 07:54.900
Uhm, no, thanks, Madge.

07:54.900 --> 07:56.450
I got a bit of a headache--

07:56.450 --> 07:57.250
MADGE: Ohh.

07:57.250 --> 07:58.640
Just maybe a bit more coffee.

07:58.640 --> 07:59.440
MADGE: OK.

08:01.790 --> 08:05.840
You're still trying
to break that 360?

08:05.840 --> 08:07.940
Kindleman called me,
said the court ought

08:07.940 --> 08:09.140
to upgrade your equipment.

08:09.140 --> 08:11.420
Go digital, make
your life easier.

08:11.420 --> 08:12.470
Yeah.

08:12.470 --> 08:17.684
Maybe make hers
easier, maybe for hers.

08:17.684 --> 08:21.230
Hmm, so dead set on winning
that competition anyway.

08:21.230 --> 08:24.030
I mean, you know you
got this job for life.

08:24.030 --> 08:27.080
Hell, Walden, I could blindfold
you and throw you down a well.

08:27.080 --> 08:30.080
You'd never miss a word.

08:30.080 --> 08:33.289
I like having something
to aim towards, you know?

08:33.289 --> 08:34.549
Call it a hobby.

08:34.549 --> 08:38.120
A nice girl would be
something to aim for, warm,

08:38.120 --> 08:39.080
animated hobby.

08:39.080 --> 08:41.960
[DOOR OPENS]

08:41.960 --> 08:44.510
Speaking of which.

08:44.510 --> 08:46.291
Here is my sweetheart.

08:46.291 --> 08:48.750
Oh.

08:48.750 --> 08:50.106
How are you, Walden?

08:50.106 --> 08:51.930
OK.

08:51.930 --> 08:53.100
I'm fine.

08:53.100 --> 08:54.870
Thank you, Mrs. Boyle.

08:54.870 --> 08:56.700
Trying convince
Walden here that he

08:56.700 --> 09:00.330
needs a warm hobby, instead of
some stenograph competition.

09:00.330 --> 09:01.140
[CHUCKLES]

09:01.140 --> 09:02.670
MADGEL I've been trying
to tell him that since he

09:02.670 --> 09:04.080
got home from college.

09:04.080 --> 09:05.730
He never listened to his mama.

09:05.730 --> 09:07.380
No chance of him hearing me.

09:07.380 --> 09:10.276
Your mama was a
fine lady, Walden.

09:10.276 --> 09:11.076
Mm.

09:11.076 --> 09:13.620
Ma'am, if she was
so fine, why did she

09:13.620 --> 09:14.910
run off with my dad's brother?

10:18.140 --> 10:23.360
Norman Casey Bolt, defiled his
little three-year-old daughter,

10:23.360 --> 10:31.050
Carmen, put her into
his oven, locked her in,

10:31.050 --> 10:35.130
and cooked her until she
was burned to the bone.

10:49.316 --> 10:52.795
[RETCHES]

10:53.789 --> 10:57.268
[SIGHS]

11:33.570 --> 11:37.530
Dear Lord in Heaven,
I usually like

11:37.530 --> 11:40.590
to kneel when I
pray to you, but I

11:40.590 --> 11:42.450
find that difficult
to do tonight

11:42.450 --> 11:48.420
when I see how that little girl
suffered while you were absent.

11:48.420 --> 11:51.630
You being God and all, I
imagine you were busy dealing

11:51.630 --> 11:55.440
with bigger things.

11:55.440 --> 11:56.760
But is there?

11:56.760 --> 11:59.490
I mean, bigger things, I mean?

11:59.490 --> 12:02.950
You think child rape and murder
would just be off the table,

12:02.950 --> 12:03.750
but--

12:03.750 --> 12:07.560
I know, I know, I know,
free will, free will.

12:07.560 --> 12:10.965
Sometimes I wish the will were
just a little bit less free.

12:13.490 --> 12:15.170
Anyway, I'm rambling now.

12:15.170 --> 12:20.960
Thank you for the food,
keeping most of us safe.

12:23.960 --> 12:27.680
You send my prayers
to little Carmen now.

12:27.680 --> 12:28.480
Good night.

12:43.100 --> 12:43.900
Oh, God.

12:47.724 --> 12:51.070
[RETCHES]

12:52.990 --> 12:55.080
Mm.

12:55.080 --> 12:55.958
Mm, hmm.

12:58.590 --> 12:59.416
Mm.

12:59.416 --> 13:00.833
WOMAN (ON PA): Dr.
Foster, you are

13:00.833 --> 13:02.090
needed in the emergency room.

13:02.090 --> 13:03.670
Dr. Foster--
- Mm-hmm.

13:03.670 --> 13:05.920
WOMAN (ON PA): --you are
needed in the emergency room.

13:05.920 --> 13:06.760
MAN: Mm-hmm.

13:06.760 --> 13:08.860
Mr. Walden Dean?

13:08.860 --> 13:10.075
Can you come with me please?

13:14.540 --> 13:16.865
Deep breath.

13:16.865 --> 13:20.260
[DEEP BREATHS]

13:22.210 --> 13:23.710
What is it you do again?

13:23.710 --> 13:27.220
Oh, uh, in layman's
terms, I'm a court reporter.

13:27.220 --> 13:30.160
More accurately, referred
to as a stenographer.

13:30.160 --> 13:33.790
So I'm quite focused for
long periods of the day.

13:33.790 --> 13:36.190
How long have you
been doing this job?

13:36.190 --> 13:39.130
Uh, about 14 years.

13:39.130 --> 13:41.710
Well, everything
checks out OK.

13:41.710 --> 13:44.880
Is there a specific reason
that brings you here today?

13:44.880 --> 13:49.790
Uhm, mostly just a
general feeling of malaise

13:49.790 --> 13:55.180
and just feeling a bit off.

13:55.180 --> 13:56.290
Have you fainted?

13:56.290 --> 13:57.400
Fallen down?

13:57.400 --> 13:58.480
Thrown up?

13:58.480 --> 14:02.320
No, no, and yes, I have
thrown up a couple of times.

14:02.320 --> 14:04.900
I just blamed it on
the stress of the job.

14:04.900 --> 14:08.110
I see in here the darkest
of the dark in court.

14:08.110 --> 14:11.250
So could that be a factor?

14:11.250 --> 14:12.480
You know what I think?

14:12.480 --> 14:15.100
I think it is stress related.

14:15.100 --> 14:17.330
I can give you something
to relax you, if you--

14:17.330 --> 14:21.755
No, no, no, I need to be sharp
for work and for other things.

14:21.755 --> 14:22.555
Thank you, Doctor.

14:28.274 --> 14:31.890
MAN: [SIGHS] Stop her.

14:31.890 --> 14:34.200
Please.

14:34.200 --> 14:36.154
Stop who?

14:36.154 --> 14:38.230
Please?

14:38.230 --> 14:39.030
Stop her.

14:41.860 --> 14:42.660
Excuse me, sir.

14:45.645 --> 14:47.020
WOMAN (ON PA):
Ms. Temple, please

14:47.020 --> 14:48.288
come to the reception desk.

14:48.288 --> 14:50.080
POLICE OFFICERS:
(SINGING) Which nobody can

14:50.080 --> 14:53.710
deny, which nobody can deny.

14:53.710 --> 14:55.150
WOMAN: My boy is missing!

14:55.150 --> 14:57.192
POLICE OFFICERS: --For
he's a jolly good fellow--

14:57.192 --> 14:58.030
My boy is gone!

14:58.030 --> 14:59.560
Somebody snatched my boy!

15:06.870 --> 15:08.670
BILL: OK.

15:08.670 --> 15:10.270
What's going on here?

15:10.270 --> 15:11.940
Well, I put him
to bed myself, Bill.

15:11.940 --> 15:14.307
I read him a story.

15:14.307 --> 15:16.890
Called him to breakfast the next
morning and went to his room,

15:16.890 --> 15:17.940
and he was gone.

15:17.940 --> 15:20.667
BILL: What makes you think he's
been abducted, Mrs. Pepper?

15:20.667 --> 15:22.500
Four boys have gone
missing from this here

15:22.500 --> 15:26.790
vicinity over the last eight
years, mostly Mexican kids,

15:26.790 --> 15:30.060
marginal and unimportant
to the law it hazard.

15:30.060 --> 15:31.500
BILL: Now, now.

15:31.500 --> 15:35.550
No kid is unimportant
to the law, Mrs. Pepper.

15:35.550 --> 15:36.660
That there computer Cal's?

15:36.660 --> 15:37.868
MR. PEPPER: Yeah, it sure is.

15:37.868 --> 15:40.140
I figured you'd
want to look at it.

15:40.140 --> 15:41.410
He don't have no password.

15:41.410 --> 15:42.210
He don't need one.

15:42.210 --> 15:43.020
He's a clean boy.

15:43.020 --> 15:43.820
BILL: All right.

15:48.710 --> 15:49.623
[SIGHS]

15:49.623 --> 15:52.040
MRS. PEPPER: We had to put the
dog down a couple of months

15:52.040 --> 15:57.180
back, couldn't
afford the vet bills.

15:57.180 --> 15:57.980
She was old.

16:01.100 --> 16:02.150
I love that dog.

16:04.570 --> 16:05.370
Yeah.

16:05.370 --> 16:06.180
No, we did.

16:10.930 --> 16:14.140
MRS. PEPPER: Bring
them home, Bill.

16:14.140 --> 16:15.310
Bring my boy home.

16:18.450 --> 16:20.850
LAWYER: Should we really
be sending this young woman

16:20.850 --> 16:24.580
to prison for doing what she can
to feed her six-month-old baby?

16:24.580 --> 16:27.000
A baby that will end
up with child services

16:27.000 --> 16:29.040
and could be adopted
by God knows who?

16:29.040 --> 16:30.454
I mean, maybe some
sick individual--

16:30.454 --> 16:31.256
Your Honor--
LAWYER: --who thinks--

16:31.256 --> 16:33.870
--she is a known prostitute
who has given at least

16:33.870 --> 16:37.440
six teenage boys around
the county herpes,

16:37.440 --> 16:38.850
and God knows what else.

16:38.850 --> 16:40.810
[OVERLAPPING SPEECH]

16:40.810 --> 16:42.670
MAN: Ooh.

16:42.670 --> 16:44.170
JUDGE BOYLE: Little
loud, everybody.

16:44.170 --> 16:45.820
Walden.

16:45.820 --> 16:46.620
Walden.

16:49.470 --> 16:52.140
Walden, did not tell
you to stop playing

16:52.140 --> 16:55.702
with that fucking machine!

16:55.702 --> 16:58.170
[BREATHING HEAVILY]

16:58.170 --> 17:00.310
Walden?

17:00.310 --> 17:01.110
Walden?

17:13.770 --> 17:17.040
Mr. Dean, how are
you feeling right now?

17:17.040 --> 17:19.630
OK, I guess.

17:19.630 --> 17:22.869
The dizziness I
had before is gone.

17:22.869 --> 17:26.650
I suppose I feel normal.

17:26.650 --> 17:28.470
I'm a neurosurgeon, Mr. Dean.

17:28.470 --> 17:31.320
I will probably want to do a
few more tests just to confirm

17:31.320 --> 17:33.510
what the CT scan revealed.

17:33.510 --> 17:35.190
CT scan?

17:35.190 --> 17:36.210
DOCTOR: Yes.

17:36.210 --> 17:38.550
What showed up
was an abnormality

17:38.550 --> 17:40.600
in your frontal lobe.

17:40.600 --> 17:43.450
It's called a meningioma.

17:43.450 --> 17:46.670
Meningioma?

17:46.670 --> 17:48.710
I've heard that word before.

17:48.710 --> 17:50.540
That's a brain tumor.

17:50.540 --> 17:52.640
I know because we had a case--

17:52.640 --> 17:55.340
I'm a stenographer--
where the suspect

17:55.340 --> 17:58.310
suffered from a meningioma.

17:58.310 --> 18:00.740
She was stealing
clothes and jewelry

18:00.740 --> 18:04.580
from a department store, acting
erratic, and causing harms,

18:04.580 --> 18:05.540
and such.

18:05.540 --> 18:08.090
At the peak of her
escalations, she

18:08.090 --> 18:10.220
had removed all of her
clothing and covered

18:10.220 --> 18:15.980
her body in her own feces before
being tased by a SWAT team.

18:15.980 --> 18:18.620
She was understandably
sectioned off

18:18.620 --> 18:22.130
to the criminal wing
of the insane asylum,

18:22.130 --> 18:23.840
where she promptly died.

18:26.370 --> 18:28.720
Jesus Christ.

18:28.720 --> 18:32.530
Does this mean that
I'm going to die?

18:32.530 --> 18:35.230
These tumors
are mostly benign.

18:35.230 --> 18:37.120
But we should operate
sooner than later

18:37.120 --> 18:39.955
because these fainting
episodes will evolve.

18:43.230 --> 18:45.570
What time is it?

18:45.570 --> 18:47.350
It's 9:00 AM.

18:47.350 --> 18:48.680
You were here overnight.

18:48.680 --> 18:50.230
Wait, what?
Oh, no!

18:50.230 --> 18:51.040
Where's my steno?

18:51.040 --> 18:52.810
I'm going to be late
for my competition.

18:52.810 --> 18:53.710
Mr. Dean, hold on.

18:53.710 --> 18:55.330
You need to take this seriously.

18:55.330 --> 18:56.470
No, I will.

18:56.470 --> 18:58.631
I just-- not right now.

18:58.631 --> 19:00.555
[DOOR OPENS]

19:00.555 --> 19:01.520
[DOOR CLOSES]

19:01.520 --> 19:03.860
The case I'm
about to read has--

19:03.860 --> 19:07.550
Mr. Dean, should you be here?

19:07.550 --> 19:09.750
Why not?

19:09.750 --> 19:10.550
Very well.

19:23.390 --> 19:26.750
KINDLEMAN: As I was saying,
this court case will read

19:26.750 --> 19:29.900
for the required 361 words.

19:29.900 --> 19:33.720
You have 60 seconds
starting now.

19:33.720 --> 19:37.340
The crime of the murder occurred
during the outdoor concert

19:37.340 --> 19:38.930
on the 1st of August 19--

19:38.930 --> 19:40.550
paramedics were
called to the scene,

19:40.550 --> 19:43.370
but the victim had suffered
a-- resulting in instant death.

19:43.370 --> 19:47.240
As a result, the outdoor event
was immediately canceled,

19:47.240 --> 19:50.280
and the police and the
suspect apprehended--

19:50.280 --> 19:51.080
time.

19:58.960 --> 20:00.530
Mm-hmm.

20:00.530 --> 20:01.330
Mm-hmm.

20:04.816 --> 20:08.302
[DOORBELL DINGS]

20:09.810 --> 20:11.640
That was impressive today.

20:11.640 --> 20:13.740
351.

20:13.740 --> 20:16.590
Anything inspire
you to up your game?

20:16.590 --> 20:21.240
Mm, possibly, I don't know.

20:21.240 --> 20:24.160
Are you sure?

20:24.160 --> 20:26.110
What are you doing?

20:26.110 --> 20:28.060
Being nosy.

20:28.060 --> 20:30.850
Are you a Savant?

20:30.850 --> 20:33.250
A Savant?

20:33.250 --> 20:34.540
No, none at all.

20:34.540 --> 20:36.820
Well, then explain yourself.

20:36.820 --> 20:38.350
Your mental acumen,
your agility,

20:38.350 --> 20:39.350
where does it come from?

20:39.350 --> 20:40.420
Where do you come from?

20:40.420 --> 20:42.253
Maybe I just want to
know who my competition

20:42.253 --> 20:45.010
is because I got 314 today,
and that's my best score yet.

20:45.010 --> 20:45.940
Oh.

20:45.940 --> 20:48.230
Oh, so you're a
professional stenographer?

20:48.230 --> 20:49.030
Yes.

20:49.030 --> 20:50.290
Well, I was.

20:50.290 --> 20:51.820
From New York City.

20:51.820 --> 20:54.700
But I came home just to
slow my life down a tad,

20:54.700 --> 20:57.550
and I use these
competitions to stay sharp

20:57.550 --> 20:59.320
and to stave off apathy.

20:59.320 --> 21:00.370
Your turn.

21:00.370 --> 21:04.790
Well, my father and his
father were both stenographers,

21:04.790 --> 21:08.380
five generations of Deans
have lived in Alexandria all

21:08.380 --> 21:10.810
the way back to the Civil War.

21:10.810 --> 21:11.740
Wow.

21:11.740 --> 21:14.300
Five generations.

21:14.300 --> 21:16.750
So this is your Daddy's machine?

21:16.750 --> 21:18.640
Yes, it is.

21:18.640 --> 21:21.040
It was.

21:21.040 --> 21:25.780
He was a very talented,
very emotional stenographer.

21:25.780 --> 21:27.500
Emotional?

21:27.500 --> 21:30.610
You think that's necessary
to be a court reporter?

21:30.610 --> 21:31.690
Well, of course.

21:31.690 --> 21:35.290
I mean, you have to feel the
words, not just type them.

21:35.290 --> 21:37.210
I knew you were a Savant.

21:37.210 --> 21:38.710
Well, you know,
my father believed

21:38.710 --> 21:41.500
words had a price, like
actions, but sometimes

21:41.500 --> 21:44.240
with greater consequence.

21:44.240 --> 21:45.040
Mm-hmm.

21:45.040 --> 21:46.120
And--

21:46.120 --> 21:48.900
Go on.

21:48.900 --> 21:49.970
You know what?

21:49.970 --> 21:51.470
You're right, ma'am.

21:51.470 --> 21:52.370
You are nosy.

21:52.370 --> 21:53.170
Mm.

21:56.502 --> 21:58.622
[DOORBELL DINGS]

21:58.622 --> 22:00.830
It's miss.

22:00.830 --> 22:03.050
It's miss, not ma'am.

22:06.940 --> 22:08.080
And these would be?

22:08.080 --> 22:10.420
These would be the
four missing boys

22:10.420 --> 22:12.640
Mrs. Pepper was talking about.

22:12.640 --> 22:16.240
All Mexican, all aged
around 9, plus 3 more,

22:16.240 --> 22:19.900
all disappeared within the
last 10 years, no results.

22:19.900 --> 22:21.073
Seven kids?

22:21.073 --> 22:22.615
SALLY: Eight if you
count Cal Pepper.

22:29.160 --> 22:29.960
Wow.

22:29.960 --> 22:31.100
Would you look at that.

22:31.100 --> 22:33.260
What?

22:33.260 --> 22:36.540
BILL: You did a really good job.

22:36.540 --> 22:39.820
Just read the damn file.

22:39.820 --> 22:42.760
[CHURCH SONG PLAYING]

22:42.760 --> 22:46.190
[INDISTINCT SPEECH]

22:54.700 --> 22:55.500
Daddy!

22:58.790 --> 22:59.590
Oh.

22:59.590 --> 23:00.390
Ohh.

23:00.390 --> 23:03.240
Oh, sorry I've
missed the rehearsal.

23:09.690 --> 23:10.870
- You're late.
- I know.

23:10.870 --> 23:11.670
I know.

23:11.670 --> 23:13.992
Sorry about that.

23:13.992 --> 23:17.373
[MUSIC PLAYING]

23:23.170 --> 23:25.350
WOMAN: Well, hello
there, handsome.

23:25.350 --> 23:27.450
(SINGING) Like a
hitman after dying.

23:30.660 --> 23:32.670
WALDEN: Hi, Dad.

23:32.670 --> 23:33.796
Walden.

23:33.796 --> 23:35.460
[CLEARS THROAT]

23:35.460 --> 23:37.500
Mind if I join you?

23:37.500 --> 23:40.290
Well, by all means.

23:40.290 --> 23:41.090
Yeah.

23:41.090 --> 23:41.890
(SINGING) Yeah.

23:45.750 --> 23:47.310
Usual soda, Walden?

23:47.310 --> 23:49.710
Actually, this evening,
I think I'll have what

23:49.710 --> 23:53.028
my dad is having, a whiskey.

23:53.028 --> 23:54.695
Good Lord, are you
dying or something?

23:54.695 --> 23:57.764
[CHUCKLES]

23:59.065 --> 23:59.865
You don't drink.

24:02.980 --> 24:03.780
I know.

24:09.027 --> 24:10.230
[SNIFFS] Oh!

24:10.230 --> 24:14.640
[CHUCKLES] Well, here's to 361.

24:14.640 --> 24:17.130
Good health, Pop.

24:17.130 --> 24:20.100
(SINGING) Call it insane--

24:20.100 --> 24:22.920
MAN: Hell boy, you just
grow a pair or something?

24:22.920 --> 24:24.625
Whiskey's a man's drink.

24:24.625 --> 24:26.250
Yeah, and how the
hell would he know?

24:30.950 --> 24:33.590
Booze.

24:33.590 --> 24:36.485
It's a good servant,
but a bad master.

24:36.485 --> 24:40.100
Is that the reason you came here
before the start of the month?

24:40.100 --> 24:41.990
No.

24:41.990 --> 24:47.380
I actually came
to see if I could

24:47.380 --> 24:51.050
convince you to move back into
the house just like old times.

24:51.050 --> 24:51.850
Hell no.

24:51.850 --> 24:53.620
Dad--

24:53.620 --> 24:55.720
I left so that you could live.

24:55.720 --> 24:57.520
[SIGHS]

24:57.520 --> 24:59.740
Mm.

24:59.740 --> 25:00.640
You know?

25:00.640 --> 25:03.910
But now, I'm not
so sure, witnessing

25:03.910 --> 25:07.060
such profoundly inconsistent
behavior, you know?

25:07.060 --> 25:12.610
I know, but Dad, I was just
thinking that maybe, you know?

25:15.470 --> 25:16.270
OK.

25:16.270 --> 25:18.150
(SINGING) --don't never come--

25:21.910 --> 25:26.210
Now, as a change
of subject, I'm

25:26.210 --> 25:28.790
going to beat that record, Pop.

25:28.790 --> 25:29.590
What for?

25:32.980 --> 25:35.440
And end up like this?

25:35.440 --> 25:37.380
Oh.

25:37.380 --> 25:40.710
JESSE: Other than
a momentary wave

25:40.710 --> 25:45.740
of hubris sweeping through,
what else does it bring?

25:45.740 --> 25:47.140
Tell me.

25:47.140 --> 25:49.270
You are just being
so negative right now.

25:49.270 --> 25:51.840
[CHUCKLES] Mm.

25:51.840 --> 25:53.000
Mm.

25:53.000 --> 25:53.838
Nope.
No.

25:53.838 --> 25:54.640
No.
No.

25:54.640 --> 25:55.510
I don't buy it.

25:55.510 --> 25:58.480
It was you that taught
me to feel the word.

25:58.480 --> 26:03.390
You, not just hear
it, not just write it.

26:03.390 --> 26:04.190
You.

26:04.190 --> 26:06.010
Stop it.

26:06.010 --> 26:08.790
No one gives a damn.

26:08.790 --> 26:09.660
Why should you?

26:19.380 --> 26:21.324
[DOOR OPENS]

26:21.324 --> 26:24.726
[DOOR CLOSES]

26:24.726 --> 26:29.460
I should-- oh,
evening, Miss Daisy.

26:29.460 --> 26:32.400
Hey, Walden.

26:32.400 --> 26:35.580
Walden, honey, are you sure you
want to be drinking that stuff?

26:35.580 --> 26:38.340
Oh, a little libation
to loosen the tongue

26:38.340 --> 26:40.920
and open the heart never
hurt anyone, Daisy.

26:40.920 --> 26:43.430
But right now, I need your
strongest over the counter

26:43.430 --> 26:44.230
for a headache--

26:44.230 --> 26:45.980
ROBBER: Give me your
fucking money bitch!

26:45.980 --> 26:46.780
OK.

26:46.780 --> 26:48.050
Back the fuck up, bruh!

26:48.050 --> 26:48.900
Hurry up!
- I am--

26:48.900 --> 26:50.650
Give me the fucking
money, and hurry up!

26:50.650 --> 26:51.890
- I'm trying.
- Check it out!

26:51.890 --> 26:53.560
I'll blow your face off!

26:53.560 --> 26:55.000
Take it all out, hurry up!
DAISY: I am.

26:55.000 --> 26:56.750
ROBBER: Give me the money.
Put it down.

26:56.750 --> 26:57.550
Give me that shit.

26:57.550 --> 26:58.350
DAISY: [GRUNTS]

26:58.350 --> 27:00.810
Stupid motherfucker!

27:00.810 --> 27:02.441
The fuck are you looking at?

27:02.441 --> 27:06.129
[GLASS SHATTERS]

27:06.129 --> 27:07.520
Oh.

27:07.520 --> 27:09.140
I'm sorry.

27:09.140 --> 27:10.070
Oh.

27:10.070 --> 27:11.115
I'm sorry.

27:11.115 --> 27:11.915
Oh.

27:15.104 --> 27:18.492
[RADIO CHATTERS]

27:22.380 --> 27:26.210
BILL: Hey, Walden.

27:26.210 --> 27:27.507
Walden, are you all right?

27:27.507 --> 27:31.370
Uhm, I feel really
bad, Detective.

27:31.370 --> 27:34.130
As you can imagine, this
is not a regular occurrence

27:34.130 --> 27:36.450
In my life.

27:36.450 --> 27:40.140
I saw that man's face shatter
into itty bitty pieces.

27:40.140 --> 27:41.398
Yeah, yeah, I hear you.

27:41.398 --> 27:43.440
I'm going to have to take
your statement, though,

27:43.440 --> 27:45.010
but it can wait till tomorrow.

27:45.010 --> 27:47.280
Uh, do you need a ride
home or something?

27:47.280 --> 27:49.095
I'd like to walk
home if that's OK.

27:51.940 --> 27:54.040
Is that misguided
gentlemen going to live?

27:56.590 --> 27:59.490
He'll live to
see you in court.

27:59.490 --> 28:04.070
Well, given his
size and disposition,

28:04.070 --> 28:07.900
I find very little
comfort in that.

28:07.900 --> 28:09.190
Good night, detectives.

28:11.280 --> 28:12.080
Not well.

28:20.490 --> 28:24.810
I have no idea where
the tools are, Walden.

28:24.810 --> 28:27.600
And why the hell do you want
to be doing the same boring job

28:27.600 --> 28:30.020
as your daddy?

28:30.020 --> 28:34.080
MRS. DEAN: [GIGGLES] I
have to go out soon, honey.

28:34.080 --> 28:38.140
I expect I won't be
back for a few hours.

28:38.140 --> 28:40.040
Tell your dad his
dinner's in the fridge.

28:40.040 --> 28:40.840
Mm?

28:45.320 --> 28:46.450
You listening to me, honey?

28:51.620 --> 28:56.170
I asked if you heard me, Walden?

28:56.170 --> 28:57.785
Your eyelashes are fake.

28:57.785 --> 28:58.585
Why?

29:17.340 --> 29:19.552
[DISTANT ARGUING]

29:19.552 --> 29:20.385
MRS. DEAN: Fuck you!

29:20.385 --> 29:21.720
MR. DEAN: Can you please just--

29:21.720 --> 29:24.385
[DISTANT ARGUING]

29:31.237 --> 29:32.450
MRS. DEAN: OK?

29:32.450 --> 29:33.720
I want a damn divorce.

29:33.720 --> 29:35.470
MR. DEAN: No, you're not-- no!
MRS. DEAN: Yes.

29:35.470 --> 29:36.950
MR. DEAN: No.
No, never.

29:36.950 --> 29:39.775
We are family.

29:39.775 --> 29:42.100
[DISTANT ARGUING]

29:47.359 --> 29:48.750
MR. DEAN: Claire, please.

29:48.750 --> 29:50.190
Claire, don't!
Claire, don't!

29:50.190 --> 29:51.000
Claire, don't go.

29:51.000 --> 29:51.800
Claire, please!

29:51.800 --> 29:53.252
[DOOR SLAMS]

29:53.252 --> 29:57.130
[DOOR OPEN]

29:57.130 --> 29:59.950
MR. DEAN: Hey, I
guess you heard that.

30:03.980 --> 30:06.530
She'll be back, son.

30:06.530 --> 30:07.330
I hope not.

30:15.328 --> 30:16.370
See you in the morning.

30:22.718 --> 30:24.760
WALDEN (VOICEOVER): I
didn't want college to end,

30:24.760 --> 30:27.580
but it kind of did when my
dad called me and told me

30:27.580 --> 30:31.510
my mom was dead, killed
by some drunk driver, who

30:31.510 --> 30:33.610
came out of nowhere.

30:33.610 --> 30:36.370
They told my dad she
never suffered, that she

30:36.370 --> 30:38.710
must have died instantly.

30:38.710 --> 30:41.290
I knew he'd find solace
in that because he

30:41.290 --> 30:43.700
never stopped missing her.

30:43.700 --> 30:46.520
This does not
happen in small towns.

30:46.520 --> 30:47.600
This might happen in LA.

30:47.600 --> 30:49.310
Does this happen in LA?
- Yep.

30:49.310 --> 30:50.110
See?

30:50.110 --> 30:54.590
It happens in LA, but it's
not supposed to happen here.

30:54.590 --> 30:56.900
What are you
doing here, Walden?

30:56.900 --> 30:59.930
You guys told me to come
in and give a statement.

30:59.930 --> 31:00.845
Is everything OK?

31:00.845 --> 31:01.960
BILL: No.

31:01.960 --> 31:05.000
No, everything is
not OK, Walden.

31:05.000 --> 31:09.040
Norman Casey Bolt got released
today on a technicality.

31:09.040 --> 31:09.840
WALDEN: What?

31:09.840 --> 31:11.540
What technicality?

31:11.540 --> 31:12.710
Brady violation.

31:12.710 --> 31:14.810
Prosecution was supposed
to turn in evidence,

31:14.810 --> 31:17.360
and they didn't, which is their
constitutional fucking duty.

31:17.360 --> 31:19.430
So now he's a free man.

31:19.430 --> 31:22.250
And adding insult to the
murder of his little girl,

31:22.250 --> 31:24.050
he's back at his own house.

31:24.050 --> 31:28.760
Hell, he even ordered
a brand new stove.

31:28.760 --> 31:30.427
Your statement on
last night's robbery--

31:30.427 --> 31:31.227
Pembleton!

31:31.227 --> 31:32.960
[SNAPS FINGERS] Get
Walden's statement,

31:32.960 --> 31:37.370
and if you excuse us, we have
to go welcome Bolt back to town.

31:37.370 --> 31:38.330
Thank you.

31:51.020 --> 31:53.420
Come see my new stove, Bill?

31:53.420 --> 31:55.430
Nah.

31:55.430 --> 31:58.340
We're just passing through.

31:58.340 --> 31:59.990
What are you doing
there, Norman?

31:59.990 --> 32:02.360
I'm just putting
these out for charity.

32:02.360 --> 32:05.180
You know, the kids around here
be needing clothes, especially

32:05.180 --> 32:07.100
in these, uh, difficult times.

32:11.020 --> 32:14.020
I just want to let
you know we're going

32:14.020 --> 32:16.435
to be passing through a lot.

32:16.435 --> 32:19.410
Do you feel me?

32:19.410 --> 32:20.210
Mm.

32:26.972 --> 32:31.630
[LAUGHS] My door is always open.

32:36.730 --> 32:40.890
Yeah, what are these
going to do for me?

32:40.890 --> 32:44.740
Are these going to carry me?

32:44.740 --> 32:45.540
No.

32:45.540 --> 32:48.730
Well, it's damn near inevitable.

32:48.730 --> 32:49.530
No.

32:54.710 --> 32:57.590
Maybe I'll fucking hit him.

32:57.590 --> 32:59.280
I could do that.

32:59.280 --> 33:03.090
Yeah, they just drilled around
your fucking thing in there.

33:03.090 --> 33:03.890
Boo!

33:07.160 --> 33:08.150
Bottoms up.

33:26.500 --> 33:30.450
[GRUNTS] Ah.

33:30.450 --> 33:31.650
What the fuck, man?

33:31.650 --> 33:34.050
Hey.

33:34.050 --> 33:36.550
You need to know
that this isn't me.

33:36.550 --> 33:40.410
But you should never have
gotten away with what you did.

33:40.410 --> 33:43.518
Cut me fucking
loose right now!

33:43.518 --> 33:49.560
You know, I came here with
the intention to scare you.

33:49.560 --> 33:55.470
And I saw with my own
eyes the degradation

33:55.470 --> 33:59.160
that that poor little child
lived in up until the moment

33:59.160 --> 34:04.950
you took her life, now
just how could anyone

34:04.950 --> 34:07.620
let their own flesh
and blood sink so

34:07.620 --> 34:13.570
hopelessly low until this,
all this became normal?

34:13.570 --> 34:15.550
This is not normal!

34:15.550 --> 34:19.650
This is the desanctification
of the human soul!

34:19.650 --> 34:23.580
And quite frankly, sir,
you have to pay for that.

34:23.580 --> 34:26.065
NORMAN: Wait, what
are you fucking-- no!

34:26.065 --> 34:26.865
Ohh!

34:30.138 --> 34:33.624
[SCREAMS]

34:42.090 --> 34:45.576
[POLICE SIREN WAILING IN
DISTANCE]

34:48.564 --> 34:52.050
[CHUCKLES]

35:01.014 --> 35:04.500
[PHONE RINGS]

35:06.990 --> 35:08.322
Hello?

35:08.322 --> 35:09.780
BILL (ON PHONE):
Walden, it's Bill.

35:09.780 --> 35:13.420
Just drop Lizzie off at school.

35:13.420 --> 35:14.220
Are you OK?

35:14.220 --> 35:16.680
Uhm, yes.

35:16.680 --> 35:20.250
Just, uh, talking
with my mouth full.

35:20.250 --> 35:21.450
Mm.

35:21.450 --> 35:23.340
BILL: I just wanted
to call you to let

35:23.340 --> 35:25.830
you know that your statement
was cleared by the DA.

35:25.830 --> 35:26.630
OK.

35:26.630 --> 35:27.700
Uh, great.

35:27.700 --> 35:28.500
Thanks.

35:28.500 --> 35:30.480
Hey.

35:30.480 --> 35:32.234
Did you hear about Bolt?

35:32.234 --> 35:34.770
Uh, Bolt?

35:34.770 --> 35:35.670
No, why?

35:35.670 --> 35:36.750
What about him?

35:36.750 --> 35:41.490
Somebody cooked his head
with his brand new stove.

35:41.490 --> 35:45.270
Jeez, to have
your head cooked?

35:45.270 --> 35:47.910
Yeah, that sounds
horrifically painful.

35:50.415 --> 35:52.290
BILL (ON PHONE): Yeah,
maybe it's just karma.

35:52.290 --> 35:55.580
Hmm, well, I don't
believe in karma,

35:55.580 --> 35:58.160
but I'm pretty sure Satan's
got himself a new chew toy.

35:58.160 --> 36:02.960
[CHUCKLES] Sure we can agree
on that part, right, Bill?

36:02.960 --> 36:04.970
If you say so, Walden.

36:04.970 --> 36:05.770
Bye, bye.

36:44.480 --> 36:48.030
Why is everyone
standing around?

36:48.030 --> 36:51.530
It's because they
know him, Detective.

36:51.530 --> 36:53.320
It's Cal.

36:53.320 --> 36:54.375
Shit.

36:54.375 --> 36:55.750
BILL: Jesus, it's
a damn tragedy.

37:01.740 --> 37:03.228
What is that?

37:03.228 --> 37:04.224
MRS. PEPPER: [SCREAMS]

37:04.224 --> 37:05.720
MR. PEPPER: Stop her.

37:05.720 --> 37:06.570
Oh, shit.

37:06.570 --> 37:07.370
Guys--

37:07.370 --> 37:10.050
[SCREAMS] Cal!

37:10.050 --> 37:11.020
Cal!

37:11.020 --> 37:12.730
God, stop.

37:12.730 --> 37:14.770
Cal!

37:14.770 --> 37:20.265
[SCREAMS] Cal!

37:23.260 --> 37:29.200
[CRYING] [SCREAMS] [CRYING]

37:29.200 --> 37:30.000
BILL: It's OK.

37:30.000 --> 37:31.284
It's OK.

37:31.284 --> 37:33.769
MRS. PEPPER: [CRYING] My boy!

37:37.750 --> 37:39.100
SALLY: What are you doing here?

37:39.100 --> 37:41.000
Well, I saw the
Peppers speed by--

37:41.000 --> 37:41.800
Oh.

37:41.800 --> 37:42.790
What's that?

37:42.790 --> 37:43.720
This?

37:43.720 --> 37:46.220
Oh, it's evidence I just pulled
it out of a dead kid's hand.

37:46.220 --> 37:47.140
Do you want to see it?

37:47.140 --> 37:47.940
Take a look.

37:50.550 --> 37:53.705
Whoever did this to
him is a monster.

37:53.705 --> 37:55.200
MRS. PEPPER: [CRYING]
- It's OK.

37:55.200 --> 37:56.000
It's OK.

37:57.868 --> 38:00.410
SALLY: Look, I need to get back
there, and you need to leave.

38:00.410 --> 38:01.610
This is a crime scene.

38:08.800 --> 38:10.630
PRIEST: Even though
we have gathered here

38:10.630 --> 38:14.740
to lament the passing
of young Cal Pepper,

38:14.740 --> 38:19.600
we must rejoice that the
Lord Jesus Christ has brought

38:19.600 --> 38:22.930
him into his heavenly Kingdom.

38:22.930 --> 38:23.810
So let us--

38:23.810 --> 38:25.300
He was murdered, Father.

38:28.450 --> 38:34.180
Cal Pepper was a
nine-year-old child,

38:34.180 --> 38:40.550
and he was brutally violated,
and choked to death.

38:40.550 --> 38:43.610
And he was one of eight
kids to suffer that same--

38:43.610 --> 38:47.450
PRIEST: Bill, perhaps the
church isn't the place

38:47.450 --> 38:49.220
for such explicit grief.

38:52.080 --> 38:55.240
I'm sorry, where?

38:55.240 --> 38:58.920
Where do we go?

38:58.920 --> 39:00.225
Isn't this the Lord's house?

39:03.000 --> 39:05.250
Why can't we lay our
pain at His door?

39:08.690 --> 39:16.160
I mean, come to me
all Ye who suffer,

39:16.160 --> 39:19.298
and I will give you comfort.

39:19.298 --> 39:23.660
You know, The Son of
Man said that, The Son.

39:26.270 --> 39:31.610
And I know eight
sons who really use

39:31.610 --> 39:33.380
His comfort right about now.

39:36.710 --> 39:37.510
Come on.

39:37.510 --> 39:38.504
Come on.

39:45.656 --> 39:46.456
Mm.

39:51.440 --> 39:57.670
You know, you know,
Cal's last supper was?

39:57.670 --> 39:59.740
It's a candy bar.

39:59.740 --> 40:00.820
Kids love candy bars.

40:09.980 --> 40:13.610
JUDGE BOYLE: All those
kids, Lord have mercy.

40:13.610 --> 40:15.950
Poor Bill pouring out
his heart like that.

40:15.950 --> 40:19.703
What in the world is
happening to our little town?

40:19.703 --> 40:21.620
It was a hell of a thing
you did the other day

40:21.620 --> 40:23.060
at that drugstore.
WALDEN: Oh, no.

40:23.060 --> 40:23.870
It was wrong.

40:23.870 --> 40:24.670
I shouldn't have.

40:24.670 --> 40:29.330
I mean, Judge, I don't
know what came over me.

40:29.330 --> 40:32.155
A big heap of bravery
is what came over you.

40:32.155 --> 40:33.530
All what's going
on in this town,

40:33.530 --> 40:35.630
I'm going to arrange a
carry permit for you.

40:35.630 --> 40:36.860
Mm.

40:36.860 --> 40:39.320
How things go at the hospital?

40:39.320 --> 40:41.360
Oh, just some routine
tests and stuff.

40:41.360 --> 40:42.380
I mean, I'm fine.

40:42.380 --> 40:46.400
But Judge, I don't
think that I need a gun.

40:46.400 --> 40:47.900
It's my town, Walden.

40:47.900 --> 40:50.780
If I say you need a
gun, you need a gun.

40:50.780 --> 40:51.650
Well--

40:51.650 --> 40:53.442
MRS. BOYLE: Better safe
than sorry, Walden.

40:53.442 --> 40:54.242
OK.

40:54.242 --> 40:55.220
[GIGGLES]

40:55.220 --> 40:56.602
We're going to lunch.

40:56.602 --> 40:57.560
You're welcome to join.

40:57.560 --> 40:59.700
Oh, no, no, thank you.

40:59.700 --> 41:00.500
Come on, honey.

41:00.500 --> 41:02.240
I'm starving.

41:02.240 --> 41:03.800
Enjoy your Sunday, Walden.

41:06.800 --> 41:09.200
JUDGE BOYLE: Stand
up, Mr. Sheldon.

41:09.200 --> 41:12.560
After some brief
deliberation on my part,

41:12.560 --> 41:16.160
and considering that the gun
you took into that theater

41:16.160 --> 41:19.850
was unloaded, I think
12 months probation

41:19.850 --> 41:20.767
should be sufficient--

41:20.767 --> 41:21.567
Yes!

41:21.567 --> 41:23.120
JUDGE BOYLE: --in this case.

41:23.120 --> 41:26.240
But Mr. Sheldon, don't
you ever let me see

41:26.240 --> 41:28.520
you in front of my court again.

41:28.520 --> 41:29.360
Do you hear me?

41:32.010 --> 41:32.940
So ruled.

41:41.310 --> 41:43.260
EMILY: I hope you
don't mind, but I

41:43.260 --> 41:44.890
wanted to see you in action.

41:44.890 --> 41:45.690
Ah.

41:45.690 --> 41:47.580
Well, why?

41:47.580 --> 41:48.910
EMILY: I don't know.

41:48.910 --> 41:50.790
I guess I had some
time on my hands,

41:50.790 --> 41:53.940
and I feel the need to
apologize for being so

41:53.940 --> 41:55.860
forward with you the other day.

41:55.860 --> 41:57.465
Calling you a Savant, and all.

41:57.465 --> 41:59.700
[LAUGHS] Oh.

41:59.700 --> 42:01.770
Savant?

42:01.770 --> 42:03.670
It's really not a problem.

42:03.670 --> 42:04.950
Great.

42:04.950 --> 42:06.750
Because I need your
help with something.

42:06.750 --> 42:07.610
Oh.

42:07.610 --> 42:08.410
With what?

42:08.410 --> 42:09.360
With whom?

42:09.360 --> 42:11.263
Oh, well, OK, with whom?

42:11.263 --> 42:13.680
See, my family's throwing
this party for my Uncle James,

42:13.680 --> 42:15.780
and I cannot handle it alone.

42:15.780 --> 42:16.950
Why not?

42:16.950 --> 42:18.850
Well, because I choose not to.

42:18.850 --> 42:19.830
Uh-huh.

42:19.830 --> 42:20.768
OK.

42:20.768 --> 42:21.810
I know what you're doing.

42:21.810 --> 42:24.030
I have work in the morning.

42:24.030 --> 42:27.930
Don't worry, I'll make sure
you're home before sunset.

42:27.930 --> 42:31.200
And you'll be doing
me a huge favor.

42:33.755 --> 42:37.010
Besides I bet that steno could
use some fresh air, being stuck

42:37.010 --> 42:40.940
in this stale courthouse
day in and day out,

42:40.940 --> 42:42.060
eternally tapped out.

42:42.060 --> 42:42.860
OK.

42:42.860 --> 42:45.570
Well, back by sunset, you say?

42:45.570 --> 42:46.370
I promise.

42:53.740 --> 42:56.080
Your family lives here?

42:56.080 --> 42:59.860
Yeah, for six generations.

42:59.860 --> 43:02.228
Beat the DEANS by one, ei?

43:02.228 --> 43:04.450
[GIGGLES]

43:04.450 --> 43:07.430
Where you been hiding
that endearing smile?

43:07.430 --> 43:09.010
Oh.

43:09.010 --> 43:10.120
Come on.

43:10.120 --> 43:13.018
Let's meet the Duperon gang.

43:13.018 --> 43:13.818
[MUSIC PLAYING]

43:13.818 --> 43:17.297
[CHATTERS]

43:22.764 --> 43:23.760
Hi.

43:23.760 --> 43:25.020
Nice to see you.

43:25.020 --> 43:25.820
WOMAN: Ah!

43:25.820 --> 43:27.110
Hi there.

43:27.110 --> 43:28.640
Jesus.
- Hi!

43:28.640 --> 43:29.510
Hi.

43:29.510 --> 43:30.310
Hi.

43:32.600 --> 43:36.650
WALDEN: This truly is a majestic
residence Mr. And Mrs. Duperon.

43:36.650 --> 43:39.350
Well, thank you, Walden.

43:39.350 --> 43:43.800
Emily has told us absolutely
nothing about you.

43:43.800 --> 43:45.320
Where are you from?

43:45.320 --> 43:47.990
Over in Alexandria, ma'am.

43:47.990 --> 43:48.950
Alexandria?

43:48.950 --> 43:50.390
Dean?

43:50.390 --> 43:54.750
Say, you wouldn't happen to be
Jesse Dean's boy, would you?

43:54.750 --> 43:55.550
Yes, sir.

43:55.550 --> 43:57.110
I am.

43:57.110 --> 44:03.290
MR. DUPERON: Jesse Dean, he was
the mildest mannered, sweetest

44:03.290 --> 44:04.980
boy in our high school.

44:04.980 --> 44:05.780
Oh.

44:05.780 --> 44:07.683
Well, you went to high
school with my Dad?

44:07.683 --> 44:08.600
MR. DUPERON: Sure did.

44:08.600 --> 44:10.910
MRS. DUPERON: Oh.

44:10.910 --> 44:13.770
Shame what that wife
of his did to him.

44:13.770 --> 44:14.570
Oh.

44:14.570 --> 44:15.980
Mm.

44:15.980 --> 44:17.960
What she do?

44:17.960 --> 44:19.680
I don't want to be
gossiping none here.

44:19.680 --> 44:20.670
But let's just say--

44:20.670 --> 44:22.010
EMILY: Hey.
[OVERLAPPING SPEECH]

44:22.010 --> 44:22.910
OK.
OK.

44:22.910 --> 44:24.920
I think that's enough.

44:24.920 --> 44:25.820
I'm sorry.

44:25.820 --> 44:28.590
As you can see nosiness is
inherent within the Duperon

44:28.590 --> 44:29.725
family.

44:29.725 --> 44:30.525
Mm.

44:30.525 --> 44:31.470
I agree, honey.

44:31.470 --> 44:33.640
That's enough, Mitchell.

44:33.640 --> 44:35.940
Please forgive him, dear.

44:35.940 --> 44:40.200
Oh, no, no, no, your husband
is right, Mrs. Duperon.

44:40.200 --> 44:43.320
My mother did not adhere
to her marriage vows,

44:43.320 --> 44:45.090
as one would hope.

44:45.090 --> 44:47.340
She was something
of a loose woman,

44:47.340 --> 44:50.700
some would even say a whore.

44:50.700 --> 44:54.200
[EXHALES] Ah, and a very
successful one at that.

44:54.200 --> 44:55.640
If you'd excuse me.

45:03.160 --> 45:06.820
Walden, how do I
even begin to apologize

45:06.820 --> 45:08.920
for my father's ignorance?

45:08.920 --> 45:09.730
Oh, no.

45:09.730 --> 45:11.515
Never apologize for a truth.

45:15.590 --> 45:20.830
You know, this house
was given to my family.

45:20.830 --> 45:22.210
Yep.

45:22.210 --> 45:25.870
Apparently, we read
the entire surrounding

45:25.870 --> 45:29.050
area of-- and you're never
going to believe this--

45:29.050 --> 45:30.710
snakes.

45:30.710 --> 45:32.350
Mm-hmm.

45:32.350 --> 45:35.680
I come from a long
line of snake charmers.

45:35.680 --> 45:40.760
[CHUCKLES] Well, tall
tales make short memories.

45:40.760 --> 45:43.990
[LAUGHS] Oh, I like that.

45:43.990 --> 45:45.580
Who said that?

45:45.580 --> 45:47.170
Walden Dean.

45:47.170 --> 45:49.300
Oh.

45:49.300 --> 45:54.330
You got any more masterful
quotes from Mr. Dean?

45:54.330 --> 45:56.400
Let me think, uhm.

45:56.400 --> 45:59.830
Two most important days in your
life are the day you're born--

45:59.830 --> 46:02.130
And the day you
find out why, OK.

46:02.130 --> 46:04.020
Are you just quoting
Mark Twain over there?

46:09.300 --> 46:10.230
Did you find out why?

46:13.670 --> 46:16.340
I didn't.

46:16.340 --> 46:18.560
Until recently.

46:18.560 --> 46:21.350
You're going to tell me?

46:21.350 --> 46:24.170
Another time.

46:24.170 --> 46:25.130
It's almost sunset.

46:33.375 --> 46:38.380
[SIGHS] Not quite
a stately mansion.

46:38.380 --> 46:42.350
Yeah, well, it is a home of
the great Savant Weldon Dean.

46:42.350 --> 46:44.640
Yeah.

46:44.640 --> 46:45.440
What?

46:48.880 --> 46:50.920
I was just thinking,
I never really

46:50.920 --> 46:54.670
put this down for that long.

46:54.670 --> 46:57.430
Thank you for the invitation.

46:57.430 --> 46:58.870
Really?

46:58.870 --> 47:03.220
After having to suffer my
father and his big old mouth?

47:03.220 --> 47:05.810
OK.

47:05.810 --> 47:07.730
Well, I'll see you
at the next round.

47:07.730 --> 47:08.990
Yeah.

47:08.990 --> 47:10.002
You broke your promise.

47:10.002 --> 47:11.585
You said you'd have
me back by sunset.

47:23.320 --> 47:24.120
Ah.

47:29.810 --> 47:30.610
Good night!

47:41.210 --> 47:43.730
BILL: Hey, George.

47:43.730 --> 47:44.960
Uh-oh.

47:44.960 --> 47:46.910
BILL: Hey, George.

47:46.910 --> 47:49.010
Oh, hi, Detective Billy.

47:49.010 --> 47:49.880
Hi.

47:49.880 --> 47:54.090
Hey, So now, you know most
everybody in Alexandria,

47:54.090 --> 47:54.890
don't you?

47:54.890 --> 47:56.390
GEORGE: Not only that.

47:56.390 --> 48:00.960
I know where they all live,
and what they do for work.

48:00.960 --> 48:01.760
OK.

48:01.760 --> 48:04.940
You seen any strange
folk hanging around?

48:04.940 --> 48:07.760
People even you've
never met before?

48:07.760 --> 48:09.230
No.

48:09.230 --> 48:12.260
I don't see anybody
outside of anybody I know,

48:12.260 --> 48:13.820
Detective Billy.

48:13.820 --> 48:17.750
If I did, I would
remember them, then they

48:17.750 --> 48:21.667
wouldn't be strangers no more.

48:21.667 --> 48:23.250
BILL: You'd tell us
if you did, right?

48:23.250 --> 48:24.150
GEORGE: Uh-huh.

48:24.150 --> 48:25.920
Sure would.

48:25.920 --> 48:28.860
SALLY: Hey, George, you
knew young Cal Pepper,

48:28.860 --> 48:30.660
didn't you, George?

48:30.660 --> 48:34.220
I don't know nothing
about what happened to Cal.

48:34.220 --> 48:36.630
Nothing.

48:36.630 --> 48:38.920
Hey, it's OK, George.

48:38.920 --> 48:39.720
OK?

48:39.720 --> 48:41.550
You have yourself a good day.

48:41.550 --> 48:44.380
Thank you.

48:44.380 --> 48:46.705
Today's court case is bad.

48:49.660 --> 48:52.600
Bad man.

48:52.600 --> 48:54.280
Very bad man.

48:57.230 --> 49:00.430
You saw that candy bar, right?

49:00.430 --> 49:02.060
Yep.

49:02.060 --> 49:03.500
I like candy bars, too.

49:06.090 --> 49:07.950
DEITRICH: Dr. Patel,
can you describe

49:07.950 --> 49:12.060
the condition you found Mr. Pym
in when you were attending him?

49:12.060 --> 49:15.000
He was in a very bad state.

49:15.000 --> 49:19.960
His heart had stopped, and
the brain had no function.

49:19.960 --> 49:23.520
Anything else
outstanding about Mr. Pym?

49:23.520 --> 49:27.390
MR. PATEL: Apart from the
cataracts in his eyes?

49:27.390 --> 49:28.190
It's over.

49:28.190 --> 49:29.960
MR. PATEL:
--Substantial bruising

49:29.960 --> 49:32.090
to his buttocks and his legs.

49:32.090 --> 49:35.480
His feet were badly
deformed from what looked

49:35.480 --> 49:37.010
like years of heavy bandaging.

49:37.010 --> 49:38.810
DEITRICH: Heavy bandaging?

49:38.810 --> 49:42.020
Any reason why his feet
were heavily bandaged?

49:42.020 --> 49:43.340
MR. PATEL: No.

49:43.340 --> 49:45.800
There was no history in
his chart showing any kind

49:45.800 --> 49:47.790
of problems in that area.

49:47.790 --> 49:49.820
So there was no real
explanation for such

49:49.820 --> 49:52.850
a sustained and
painful treatment.

49:52.850 --> 49:55.610
DEITRICH: Did you know, Dr.
Patel, that Mr Pym was not

49:55.610 --> 49:58.640
the only patient at the
blessed retirement facility

49:58.640 --> 50:01.670
to have sustained such
terrible injuries?

50:01.670 --> 50:04.460
MR. PATEL: There were
whispers about the BRF,

50:04.460 --> 50:05.940
but not much more than that.

50:05.940 --> 50:10.520
So you aren't aware that
Chief attending nurse, Katherine

50:10.520 --> 50:13.070
Mills, was overseeing
these patients,

50:13.070 --> 50:17.090
and was caught by the son of
one patient, a Mr. Andrews,

50:17.090 --> 50:19.370
slapping his father
across the face

50:19.370 --> 50:20.675
for not taking his medication?

50:20.675 --> 50:22.070
Objection, Your Honor!

50:22.070 --> 50:24.440
As bad as slapping anyone
across the face is,

50:24.440 --> 50:27.090
it doesn't rise to a
level of probable cause

50:27.090 --> 50:28.590
that my client
nurse Mills, who is

50:28.590 --> 50:31.830
25 years of impeccable service
in the medical profession,

50:31.830 --> 50:34.500
systematically tortured his
unfortunate patients who

50:34.500 --> 50:37.170
subsequently died from nothing
to do with bandaged feet

50:37.170 --> 50:38.010
or bruised buttocks.

50:38.010 --> 50:41.240
| of which can be explained with
justifiable medical reasoning.

50:41.240 --> 50:44.160
I'm sorry, Your Honor,
but defense is deflecting

50:44.160 --> 50:47.100
from an observation of
violence, which clearly lends

50:47.100 --> 50:49.720
itself to a mode of behavior.

50:49.720 --> 50:52.960
Ms. Deitrich, did
anybody actually see

50:52.960 --> 50:56.740
nurse Mills binding
these poor people's feet

50:56.740 --> 50:59.080
or whipping them with a--

50:59.080 --> 51:01.660
Leather belt?

51:01.660 --> 51:04.390
No, Your Honor, no witnesses.

51:04.390 --> 51:06.190
I'm sorry, but I--

51:06.190 --> 51:09.670
I just can't see your
stretch of logic here.

51:09.670 --> 51:13.900
Owing to Chief nurse
Mills impeccable record,

51:13.900 --> 51:17.830
and the lack of
any probable cause,

51:17.830 --> 51:23.890
or actual evidence, no
eyewitnesses, no leather belt,

51:23.890 --> 51:27.790
I see no alternative, but to,
uh, grant the defense's motion

51:27.790 --> 51:29.230
for dismissal of all charges.

51:35.550 --> 51:38.970
Walden, how have
you been feeling?

51:38.970 --> 51:42.120
If it is, just want you
to know I'm here for you.

51:42.120 --> 51:44.280
Well, I told you the
other day, Judge, I mean,

51:44.280 --> 51:46.110
there's nothing wrong with me.

51:46.110 --> 51:51.240
Just stress, trying to impose
itself on my disposition.

51:51.240 --> 51:55.260
They're probably just trying to
beat that stupid steno record.

51:55.260 --> 51:57.960
Do yourself a favor, son,
and quit that damn competition

51:57.960 --> 51:59.160
right now.

51:59.160 --> 52:03.160
Well, I can't.

52:03.160 --> 52:06.160
I met someone there.

52:06.160 --> 52:08.560
A very nice young woman.

52:08.560 --> 52:11.140
Well, I will be damned.

52:11.140 --> 52:12.400
[CHUCKLES]

52:12.400 --> 52:14.050
How about that?

52:14.050 --> 52:15.760
Well, you sneaky son of a gun.

52:15.760 --> 52:17.140
Don't.

52:17.140 --> 52:21.205
No wonder you're
all bent out of shape.

52:21.205 --> 52:22.300
Speaking of guns?

52:22.300 --> 52:24.790
Mm.

52:24.790 --> 52:26.140
Still feels kind of weird.

52:26.140 --> 52:29.830
I mean, it's not really me.

52:29.830 --> 52:31.675
You just watch your
back now, you hear?

52:31.675 --> 52:32.570
Oh, yes, sir.

52:32.570 --> 52:33.370
All right.

52:39.623 --> 52:42.990
[BEEPS]

52:45.095 --> 52:45.895
Mm.

53:14.140 --> 53:15.940
This room is
supposed to be empty.

53:15.940 --> 53:18.610
You can't be in here.

53:18.610 --> 53:19.915
Are you hearing me?

53:22.810 --> 53:24.700
Who the fuck are you?

53:24.700 --> 53:26.200
The stenographer.

53:30.136 --> 53:35.287
[MUMBLES] Not exactly
a pedicure, but--

53:35.287 --> 53:36.285
[GRUNTS]

53:36.285 --> 53:39.240
[GROANS]

53:39.240 --> 53:40.040
Well--

53:40.040 --> 53:42.920
[GROANS]

53:43.720 --> 53:47.477
Do you know what Mr.
Pym's last words were?

53:47.477 --> 53:48.850
[MUMBLES]

53:48.850 --> 53:51.850
Well, I do because
he said them to me.

53:51.850 --> 53:54.440
He said, "Stop her.

53:54.440 --> 53:56.450
Oh, please?"

53:56.450 --> 53:57.250
[MUMBLES]

53:57.250 --> 54:00.976
I feel compelled to
comply with his plea.

54:00.976 --> 54:03.970
MILLS: [MUMBLES]

54:03.970 --> 54:05.920
WALDEN: I'm going
to give you a chance

54:05.920 --> 54:10.190
to come clean and confess
to all the years of abuse

54:10.190 --> 54:14.260
you have inflicted on
the elderly, the infirm,

54:14.260 --> 54:17.710
and the unprotected.

54:17.710 --> 54:23.100
You did devilishly
murder, Mr. Pym, correct?

54:23.100 --> 54:23.900
[MUMBLES]

54:23.900 --> 54:28.370
You have snuffed out the lives
of countless others, have you

54:28.370 --> 54:29.265
not?

54:29.265 --> 54:31.490
[MUMBLES]

54:31.490 --> 54:33.050
Good.

54:33.050 --> 54:36.800
I'm glad you got
that off your chest.

54:36.800 --> 54:39.680
Boy, oh, boy, you
just couldn't resist

54:39.680 --> 54:43.490
flaunting a souvenir of the
pain you caused, could you?

54:43.490 --> 54:47.180
The stories this
bloodstained belt could tell.

54:47.180 --> 54:50.610
You see this spot right here?

54:50.610 --> 54:51.590
This one's for you.

54:54.410 --> 55:04.590
MILLS: [GROANS] [MUMBLES]
[MUMBLED SCREAMS]

55:15.270 --> 55:18.990
KINDLEMAN: That resulted in
between 3,000 and 5,000 people

55:18.990 --> 55:21.960
accused of heresy
and/or witchcraft

55:21.960 --> 55:26.920
was finally abandoned
July 15, 1834.

55:26.920 --> 55:27.720
Time.

55:32.050 --> 55:36.730
329.

55:36.730 --> 55:38.890
Care to tell me?

55:38.890 --> 55:43.740
The same, 329.

55:43.740 --> 55:46.200
Mm, I see.

55:46.200 --> 55:51.000
Synchronicity prevails,
congratulations.

55:51.000 --> 55:52.920
Every bone in
both feet is broken.

55:52.920 --> 55:54.390
Some of them was just splinters.

56:01.853 --> 56:03.020
Cotton ball in the nostrils.

56:05.680 --> 56:08.675
Jesus, what a fucking mess.

56:08.675 --> 56:09.475
Sorry.

56:12.820 --> 56:21.530
